Plotting Heat-Map for Missing Values

# Create a matrix of missing values
missing_matrix <- is.na(df1)

# Convert matrix to data frame
missing_df <- as.data.frame(missing_matrix)

# Reshape data to long format
missing_long <- missing_df %>%
  mutate(row = 1:nrow(.)) %>%
  gather(variable, value, -row) %>%
  filter(value == TRUE) %>%
  mutate(value = 1)

# Plot heatmap
ggplot(missing_long, aes(variable, row, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red", na.value = "white") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Heatmap of Missing Values", x = "Variable", y = "Observation") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1))

Initial Data Exploration

  1. Distribution of review ratings:
rating_colors <- function(rating) {
  if (rating == 5) {
    return("#f8b96d")
  } else if (rating == 4) {
    return("#00BFC4")
  } else {
    return("#F8766D")
  }
}

# Create a new column in the data frame with custom colors based on rating values
df1_clean1$rating_color <- sapply(df1_clean1$reviews.rating, rating_colors)

# Bar plot with custom colors
ggplot(df1_clean1, aes(x = reviews.rating, fill = rating_color)) +
  geom_bar(color = "black", width = 0.7) +
  scale_fill_identity() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Ratings", x = "Rating", y = "Frequency") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

The visual represents the distribution of 34,064 customer ratings, with a rating scale from 1 (least favorable) to 5 (most favorable). A clear majority of customers have a positive perception of the products, as evidenced by the high percentage of ratings at the top end of the scale. Specifically, 68.7% of customers assigned the highest rating of 5, while 24.9% opted for a rating of 4. On the other hand, lower ratings constitute a small portion of the total, with 4.3% at 3, 1.1% at 2, and only 1% at the lowest rating of 1. This distribution highlights the overall customer satisfaction with the products, as most ratings are concentrated at 4 and 5.

The visual shows the distribution of reviews across different brands.

  1. The majority of reviews (82.6%) were for ‘Amazon’ products, with 28,124 reviews, indicating a strong interest in the Amazon brand among consumers.

  2. The second-highest number of reviews (14.8%) was for ‘Amazon Fire TV,’ which had 5,052 reviews, showing that it is also a popular product line.

  3. ‘Amazon Echo’ and ‘Amazon Fire’ received comparatively fewer reviews, with only 1.9% (633 reviews) and 0.7% (255 reviews) of the total, respectively. This suggests that these brands might be less popular or have a smaller customer base compared to Amazon and Amazon Fire TV products.

On the other hand, the visual also reveals that ‘Amazon Echo’ has the highest proportion of dissatisfied customers, with a not recommended rate of 6.96%. The data suggests that the company may need to focus on improving customer satisfaction for the ‘Amazon Echo’ and ‘Amazon Fire’ product lines, as they have the highest proportion of not recommended reviews.

  1. Time series plot of review ratings:
df1_clean1$reviews.date <- as.Date(df1_clean1$reviews.date)

rating_time_series <- df1_clean1 %>%
  group_by(reviews.date) %>%
  summarize(avg_rating = mean(reviews.rating, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(rating_time_series, aes(x = reviews.date, y = avg_rating)) +
  geom_line(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Average Rating Over Time",
       x = "Date",
       y = "Average Rating") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The time series plot of review ratings provides insights into the trends and changes in customer satisfaction over time. From the visualization, we can observe the following:

  1. Between 2014-10-24 and the end of 2017, the average rating mostly fluctuated between 4 and 5, indicating that the customers generally had a positive experience with the products. There were only a few instances where the average rating dipped to around 3, and even fewer instances where it reached 1 or 2.

  2. As we enter 2018, there appears to be a structural break in the pattern, with the smoothing curve (red dashed line) indicating a downward trend in the average rating. This suggests that in 2018, there was an increase in the number of lower ratings (1 or 2) compared to higher ratings (4 and 5).

This time series plot highlights the need to investigate further into the possible causes of the decline in customer satisfaction in 2018. Understanding the factors behind this trend can help improve the products and marketing strategies to enhance customer satisfaction in the future.

10.Word cloud for most common words in reviews:

# Create a corpus from the 'reviews.text' column
reviews_corpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(df1_clean1$reviews.text))

# Pre-process the text data
reviews_corpus <- tm_map(reviews_corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
reviews_corpus <- tm_map(reviews_corpus, removeNumbers)
reviews_corpus <- tm_map(reviews_corpus, removePunctuation)
reviews_corpus <- tm_map(reviews_corpus, stripWhitespace)
reviews_corpus <- tm_map(reviews_corpus, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
reviews_corpus <- tm_map(reviews_corpus, stemDocument)

# Create a document-term matrix
dtm <- DocumentTermMatrix(reviews_corpus)

# Calculate word frequencies
word_freqs <- colSums(as.matrix(dtm))

# Sort word frequencies in decreasing order
word_freqs_sorted <- sort(word_freqs, decreasing = TRUE)

# Create a word cloud
wordcloud(words = names(word_freqs_sorted), freq = word_freqs_sorted, min.freq = 50,
          max.words = 100, random.order = FALSE, colors = brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

The word cloud provides a visual representation of the most frequently mentioned words in the reviews. The size of each word represents its frequency in the dataset. From this visualization, we can observe the following:

  1. The words ‘great’ and ‘use’ are the most frequently mentioned, indicating that many customers find the product to be of high quality and useful.

  2. The words ‘tablet’ and ‘love’ are the second most common, suggesting that customers are expressing their appreciation for the tablets.

  3. Other common words include ‘amazon’, ‘bought’, ‘good’, ‘read’, ‘work’, ‘kindle’, and ‘one’. These words are smaller in size compared to the top two, but still significant in frequency, highlighting various aspects of the products, such as the brand, usage, and purchasing experiences.

This word cloud helps us gain a quick understanding of the customers’ opinions and the key themes present in the reviews.

11. Distribution of rating over Days of the week and time of the day

# Create a copy of the dataset
df1_copy <- df1

# Convert the 'reviews.dateAdded' column in the copied dataset to a POSIXct type
df1_copy$reviews.dateAdded <- as.POSIXct(df1_copy$reviews.dateAdded, format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S")

# Extract the time information from the 'reviews.dateAdded' column in the copied dataset
df1_copy$time <- format(df1_copy$reviews.dateAdded, format = "%H:%M:%S")

# Create a new dataset with the extracted time information
time_data <- data.frame(time = df1_copy$time)
# Add the 'weekday' column to df1_copy
df1_copy$weekday <- weekdays(df1_copy$reviews.dateAdded)

df1_copy$hour_12 <- format(df1_copy$reviews.dateAdded, format = "%I %p")
df1_aggregated <- df1_copy %>%
  group_by(weekday, hour_12) %>%
  summarize(avg_rating = mean(reviews.rating, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'weekday'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(df1_aggregated, aes(x = hour_12, y = weekday, fill = avg_rating)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white", size = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("white", "darkred")) +
  labs(title = "Heatmap of Ratings by Weekday and Hour",
       x = "Hour of the Day",
       y = "Weekday",

The scatter plot visualizes the relationship between ‘reviews.rating’ and ‘reviews.numHelpful’ for each of the five groups (Tblts, AmzDvcs, Accz, Elec, and OffnBuss). The plot shows the distribution of data points based on the ratings given by reviewers and the number of helpful reviews for each product in these groups.

From the plot, we can observe the following:

  1. There seems to be a positive trend between the ‘reviews.rating’ and ‘reviews.numHelpful’ for all groups. This indicates that as the rating of a product increases, the number of helpful reviews also tends to increase.

  2. The distribution of data points varies among the different groups. Some groups have more data points, while others have fewer. This reflects the differences in the number of products and reviews in each group.

  3. There might be some outliers in the data, as we can see a few data points with very high numbers of helpful reviews. These outliers might represent extremely popular or controversial products that received a lot of attention and feedback from users.

  4. The color-coding by group helps in identifying any potential patterns or differences among the groups in terms of the relationship between ratings and helpful reviews. In this plot, it seems that the relationship is similar across all groups, with no distinct differences among them. In summary, the scatter plot suggests a positive relationship between the ‘reviews.rating’ and ‘reviews.numHelpful’ across all groups. However, the strength of this relationship and the presence of any distinct patterns among the groups would require further statistical analysis to confirm.

The bar plot displays the point-biserial correlation coefficients between each of the five group variables (Tblts, AmzDvcs, Accz, Elec, and OffnBuss) and the binary variable ‘reviews.doRecommend’. The point-biserial correlation is used to measure the strength and direction of the association between a continuous and a binary variable.

From the plot, we can observe the following:

  1. Tblts: This group has a weak negative correlation (-0.039) with ‘reviews.doRecommend’, which indicates that products in this group have a slight tendency to be less recommended by reviewers.

  2. AmzDvcs: This group also shows a weak negative correlation (-0.018) with ‘reviews.doRecommend’, implying that products in this group are also slightly less likely to be recommended.

  3. Accz: This group has a weak positive correlation (0.010) with ‘reviews.doRecommend’, suggesting that products in this group are slightly more likely to be recommended by reviewers.

  4. Elec: This group displays a weak positive correlation (0.017) with ‘reviews.doRecommend’, indicating that products in this group tend to be more recommended by reviewers.

  5. OffnBuss: This group has a higher positive correlation (0.036) with ‘reviews.doRecommend’ than the other groups, implying that products in this group are more likely to be recommended by reviewers compared to the other groups.

Overall, the correlations between the group variables and ‘reviews.doRecommend’ are all weak, suggesting that the relationship between the group membership and the likelihood of a product being recommended is not strong

Product Group Summary: Reviews, Recommendations, and Average Ratings (Pivot table)

# Calculate the required summary statistics for each group
pivot_data <- df2 %>%
  group_by(Tblts, AmzDvcs, Accz, Elec, OffnBuss) %>%
  summarise(
    Total_Reviews = n(),
    Recommended_Count = sum(reviews.doRecommend == TRUE),
    Average_Rating = mean(reviews.rating, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Group = case_when(
      Tblts == 1 ~ "Tblts",
      AmzDvcs == 1 ~ "AmzDvcs",
      Accz == 1 ~ "Accz",
      Elec == 1 ~ "Elec",
      OffnBuss == 1 ~ "OffnBuss"
    ),
    Percent_Recommended = (Recommended_Count / Total_Reviews) * 100,
    Not_Recommended_Percentage = 100 - Percent_Recommended
  ) %>%
  select(Group, Percent_Recommended, Not_Recommended_Percentage, Average_Rating, Total_Reviews)

The matrix has 34,064 documents (rows) and 17,601 features (columns). The sparsity of the matrix is 99.92%, meaning that most of the elements in the matrix are zeros.

In the TF-IDF matrix, each row represents a document (in this case, a review), and each column represents a unique word (feature) found in the dataset. The values in the matrix represent the importance of each word in a specific document. A higher value for a word in a particular document means that the word is more significant in that document. Conversely, a value of zero means that the word does not appear in the document or has low importance.

The matrix helps in understanding the content of the reviews and can be used for various text analysis tasks, such as sentiment analysis, topic modeling, or document classification.

The output shows the proportion of 5-star ratings when sentiment scores for the review text and title are positive or negative/zero. The results can be interpreted as follows:

  • When the sentiment score for the review text (snt_scr_text) is positive, approximately 70.46% of the ratings are 5-star ratings.
  • When the sentiment score for the review title (snt_scr_title) is positive, approximately 70.36% of the ratings are 5-star ratings.
  • When the sentiment score for the review text (snt_scr_text) is negative or zero, approximately 53.27% of the ratings are 5-star ratings.
  • When the sentiment score for the review title (snt_scr_title) is negative or zero, approximately 61.07% of the ratings are 5-star ratings.

These results indicate that there is a positive relationship between sentiment scores and the likelihood of a 5-star rating. When the sentiment scores for the review text and title are positive, a higher proportion of the ratings are 5-star compared to when the sentiment scores are negative or zero. This suggests that customers tend to give higher ratings when their reviews express positive sentiments.

In summary, the system is more likely to make a recommendation when the sentiment scores for both text and title are positive, compared to when the sentiment scores are negative or neutral.

Balancing the dep var ‘reviews.doRecommend’ 50-50. Method used ‘random oversampling’.

Original distribution was 96% Recommended and 4% not recommend. Changed it 50% recommended 50% not recommened.Balanced the training dataset by oversampling the minority class to achieve an equal proportion of “True” and “False” observations.

After balaning train_df3_b1 observations = 45,466

Balancing the training data.

custom_sampling <- function(x, y) {
  # Get the indices of the minority class (FALSE)
  class_false_indices <- which(y == "FALSE")
  
  # Get the indices of the majority class (TRUE)
  class_true_indices <- which(y == "TRUE")
  
  # Oversample the minority class (FALSE)
  oversampled_false_indices <- sample(class_false_indices, length(class_true_indices) * 0.8, replace = TRUE)
  
  # Combine the indices of the majority class (TRUE) and the oversampled minority class (FALSE)
  all_indices <- c(class_true_indices, oversampled_false_indices)
  
  # Return the indices
  return(all_indices)
}

set.seed(123) # For reproducibility
train_indices <- createDataPartition(df3_b2$rating_is_5, p = 1, list = FALSE, times = 1)
balanced_train_indices <- custom_sampling(df3_b2, df3_b2$rating_is_5[train_indices])
train_df3_b2_balanced <- df3_b2[balanced_train_indices, ]

Balancing the training dataset ‘train_df3_b3’.

We have used custom-oversampling in this to avoid the problem of over-fitting. match the majority class more closely not completely.

Oversampled the minority classes by sampling their indices with replacement. For class “4”, it oversamples 3 times its original length, while for class “below_4”, it oversamples 6 times its original length.

train_df3_b3$rating_category <- as.factor(train_df3_b3$rating_category)
custom_sampling <- function(x, y) {
  # Get the indices of the minority classes
  class_4_indices <- which(y == "4")
  class_below_4_indices <- which(y == "below_4")
  
  # Oversample the minority classes
  oversampled_4_indices <- sample(class_4_indices, length(class_4_indices) * 3, replace = TRUE)
  oversampled_below_4_indices <- sample(class_below_4_indices, length(class_below_4_indices) * 4, replace = TRUE)
  
  # Combine the indices of the majority class and the oversampled minority classes
  all_indices <- c(which(y == "5"), oversampled_4_indices, oversampled_below_4_indices)
  
  # Return the indices
  return(all_indices)
}
set.seed(123) # For reproducibility
train_indices <- createDataPartition(train_df3_b3$rating_category, p = 1, list = FALSE, times = 1)
balanced_train_indices <- custom_sampling(train_df3_b3, train_df3_b3$rating_category[train_indices])
train_df3_b3_balanced <- train_df3_b3[balanced_train_indices, ]
